Californians made history by approving funding for embryonic stem cell research, defying President Bush's ban.
Proponents believe this decision will accelerate the search for cures to diseases like cancer and Alzheimer's.
The measure aims to establish California as a global hub for stem cell research.
The passing of Proposition 71 allocated nearly $3 billion over a decade for this cause.
Additionally, a study on dopamine's impact on Parkinson's patients sheds light on learning mechanisms.
Stem cell research advocates, including Nancy Reagan and senators, emphasize the potential for disease cures.
The debate continues on the ethical implications and scientific advancements in this field.
